The ng-app directive defines an AngularJS application.

The ng-model directive binds the value of HTML controls (input, select, textarea) to application data.

The ng-bind directive binds application data to the HTML view.

The ng-init directive initializes AngularJS application variables.

The module is a container for the different parts of an application.

The module is a container for the application controllers.

An AngularJS module defines an angularjs  application.

we define controller and module

AngularJS lets you extend HTML with new attributes called Directives.

AngularJS has a set of built-in directives which offers functionality to your applications.

AngularJS also lets you define your own directives.

<script>

  var app = angular.module("myApp", []);

  app.controller("myCtrl", function($scope) {
      $scope.firstName = "John";
      $scope.lastName = "Doe";
  });

</script>

ng-repeat Example:
<ul>
    <li ng-repeat="x in names">
      {{ x }}
    </li>
  </ul>
  
  
  When naming a directive, you must use a camel case name, w3TestDirective, but when invoking it, 
  you must use - separated name, w3-test-directive:
  
  
  
